History and Reflection

How Crowded?
The web site “insideschools.org” reports the “building was meant to house 650 kids”.  “Meant” is the operative word here for 650 had to be the intent when the building was constructed at the end of the third decade of the last century.  Suggested by the statement is a situation likely to mortify most of us with the thought of oppressive overcrowding rather than inspire us by a community of parents and educators determination to teach and to learn under challenged conditions.

My nine years at ‘124’ covered the late‘40’s through the mid ‘50’s.  Simple extrapolation of the headcount of my graduating class picture suggests a K-8 student population of about 700 pupils.  A similar headcount of the ’61 graduating class points to a 33% student enrollment growth in just five years.  The decade of the 1950’s was a period of explosive population growth in the city’s outer boroughs and surrounding suburbs.  I have no substantiating data but the social upheaval of the time and my own memories lead me to conclude my class was likely also on the order of 33% larger the class five years before its time.  The old building would have indeed been under utilized, back then.

The Harry Potter Prelude
The west wing addition to PS 124 was incomprehensible back then.  Numerous empty classrooms at the far ends of unlighted hallways sat in shadowy silence.  Nooks and crannies in that building beckoned unto me, but those fascinating places of intrigue were locked and off limits to the dangerously curious like me.  Fortunately, the terrific architectural features were out in the open and therefore mine to enjoy to the fullest.  Stepping out on that second floor front balcony to retrieve a flowerpot under wary eyes of teachers and the wide eyes of fellow students was a thrilling experience.  I was a really little guy back then so my recall of the physical world is that of space so much bigger then it was in actual fact.  The dual front entrance atriums contained open stairways, both broad and grand and I loved the tall and sometimes arched windows of the great rooms of the auditorium, the gyms and the first floor lunch areas.

Scandal!
Too young to comprehend the issues of the time, I recall an attempt in the early 50’s to close the school.  An obligatory community meeting was called wherein city/education officials expected to deliver the harsh facts-of-life in cold perfunctory style to a gullible and complicit collection of simple homeowners.  Among the citizenry someone or some group had done homework and came prepared.  During the public meeting errors in the ‘facts’ were exposed.  I am not sure of the details, but it may have involved faulty, doctored or missing maps.  The meeting imploded, the humiliated officials routed, and plans to close the school were never raised again.  Wish my parents were still alive to have them explain that story to me one more time.  Additional information regarding moment of victory for the people would be welcomed.

Race and Relations
The student body was all white with Italian-Americans the apparent ethnic majority.  African-Americans lived in a far away place known as Jamaica, just accrosse the newly built Van Wyck Expressway.  Late in 8th grade the first black students were admitted, one boy and one girl. Viewed with distant curiosity they did not absorb into the existing social order of our class but I recall no expressed bigotry or vitriolic racism.  Understandably, they were shy and perhaps apprehensive but any student would have felt awkward and out of place entering a class late in the school year where the already forged friendships reached back to kindergarten.

Students were not the first African American in our school.  Somewhere in the middle grades word came through the grapevine that Miss. Zuill was “Coming back”.  An aunt (born circa 1918) informed us that Miss Zuill had once been her teacher. That would link this educator to the school’s very beginning.  I was terrified of the woman, not because she was black but because of the stories of her strict manners.  Indeed, she had a hard veneer, but she was fair, she was professional and she was always confident.  As we came to know her we learned that while we had better not challenge her we could also find solace in at least knowing that she did not take herself too seriously.  In the midst of an oft-heard recital (The Midnight Ride of Paul Revere) or during stern rhetoric she would sometimes burst into brief but brilliant smiles that boarded on giggles.

All has changed.  That lonely schoolhouse on the old Bergen road and isolated by the Belt parkway built in the late 1930’s is relevant and vibrant, bursting at it’s seams…or so it seems. Today, it has a student body twice the number I knew.  The all white student population has dwindled to a mere 3%.  So what!  How delightful to read the performance reports found on the various web sites that report this information. If there were formal reviews in my day to determine student learning I never knew PS124’s standings.  All I knew was what I accomplished there was enough (barely) to get me into high school. 

Legacies and Evolution
Urban and close-in suburban upbringing in a pluralistic society is an enriching and enlightening experience.  It can also be difficult for the nostalgic inclined.  To flourish in whatever the future holds for us both individually and as a community we must welcome the inevitable if we have any hope to help form it. 






















